In acute triangle $ABC$, $\angle A = 68^\circ$.  Let $O$ be the circumcenter of triangle $ABC$.  Find $\angle OBC$, in degrees.

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, O;

A = (1,2);
B = (0,0);
C = (3,0);
O = circumcenter(A,B,C);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(circumcircle(A,B,C));
draw(B--O);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
dot("$O$", O, NE);
[/asy]

inference:
Since $O$ is the circumcenter of triangle $ABC$, $OA = OB = OC$.  Therefore, triangle $OAB$ is isosceles, so $\angle OBA = \angle OAB$.  Also, $\angle AOB = 2 \angle ACB$ (the central angle is twice the inscribed angle), so $\angle OBA = \frac{1}{2} (180^\circ - \angle AOB) = 90^\circ - \angle ACB$.

